p-NP is extremely challenging to remove from groundwater because of its long-lasting durability, which is the most hazardous among the pollutants. Developing a strategy to detect trace levels is of utmost importance in the current situation. In the current work, we performed the N-CDs sensitivity against p-NP. Fig. 7
 (a) shows the decline in N-CDs fluorescence intensity with more or increasing concentration of p-NP. This variation is a linear function between the emission intensity and concentration of p-NP in the 0.25 μM to 25 μM. Herein, F and Fo indicate the emission intensity of N-CDs in the presence and absence of pollutant p-NP at 450 nm. The obtained slope of this linear equation fitting is F/Fo = −0.0193 [p-NP μM] + 0.9892, with an excellent correlation coefficient of 0.9943 (R2). Fig. 7 (b) inset shows the influence of p-NP on the N-CDs fluorescence variation over the full range from 0.25 to 125 μM concentration. The detection limit was calculated for the same, and the obtained Limit of Detection (LOD) was 0.02 μM or 20 nM (3σ/k). This observed LOD was compared with the reported literature (Table 1
). This proves that this is one of the efficient ways to sense the p-NP. This study shows that, with further development at the industrial scale, synthesized CDs could be a different source for sensing the pollutant p-NP and other advantages.
